You need to change one line in the code.

    res = val[i] / val[i + 1];

you are using `+ 2` for index but the operand is in `op[]` and not in `val[]`

In `res=val[i]/val[i+2]`, you are dividing the value at `i` by the value at `i+2`. This is not correct because it may result in an `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` if `i+2` is beyond the length of the array.

Also,result of the division is not properly assigned back into the `val` array after the operation.

You are trying to perform operations and shrink the arrays in one pass. This is not an effective approach. It would be more easy to first apply all division and multiplication operations then proceed with addition and subtraction.


```
package trial;
import java.util.Scanner;
public class trial {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        float[] val = new float[10];
        char[] op = new char[10];
        int lim;
        Scanner sc= new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println(&quot;how many operands&quot;);
        lim = sc.nextInt();
        for(int i = 0; i &lt; lim; i++) {
            System.out.println(&quot;enter a number&quot;);
            val[i] = sc.nextFloat();
            if(i != lim - 1) {
                System.out.println(&quot;enter the operation(+,-,/,*)&quot;);
                op[i] = sc.next().charAt(0);
            }
        }

        // Perform the operations following BODMAS rules
        for(int i = 0; i &lt; lim-1; i++) {
            if(op[i] == &#39;/&#39;) {
                val[i+1] = val[i] / val[i+1];
                op[i] = &#39; &#39;;
            }
            else if(op[i] == &#39;*&#39;) {
                val[i+1] = val[i] * val[i+1];
                op[i] = &#39; &#39;;
            }
        }
        for(int i = 0; i &lt; lim-1; i++) {
            if(op[i] == &#39;+&#39;) {
                val[i+1] = val[i] + val[i+1];
            }
            else if(op[i] == &#39;-&#39;) {
                val[i+1] = val[i] - val[i+1];
            }
        }
        System.out.println(&quot;Result is &quot;+val[lim-1]);
    }
}
